This food is fantastic. I friend had their food catered for a party this summer and I’ve been hooked ever since. The portions are very large with a mixture of several Mediterranean dishes. The chicken shawarma is delicious and however they prepare their rice is amazing. The falafel is tasty and the texture is perfect. My favorite thing though is their special hot sauce. It’s the most delicious hot sauce I’ve ever had.  I travel from the south loop and fight for parking just to pick up their food and I never regret it.

Came in for the free Falafel sandwich promotion. I would go again and pay full price! It was delicious, the service was good, and the place looks clean. My wife and I thought it was better than nearby Sultan's. Their spicy sauce is just hot enough with a little sweetness to take the edge off. Almost couldn't decide whether I wanted more sauce or to just appreciate the falafel sandwich and the interplay of the toppings: purple cabbage, seasoned raw onions, hummus, tahini, cucumber salad etc. The feta fries left something to be desired but the fries themselves were good and crispy. We didn't get drinks bc there wasn't an option that isn't overly sweet. Hey Rumi owners, add a lightly sweetened drink to the menu for those of us who like a beverage but don't want the sweet stuff!

I don't usually find myself this far up North on Milwaukee, though as the Blue O'Hare bound currently isn't stopping at my normal stop, I have been walking by Rumi on my way home, and I finally decided to give it a try.  The staff is very friendly, and helpful, I decided on the "All-in Platter" Plate to get a feel of the diversity of items on their menu. This seems to consist of Gyro Meat, Chicken Swarma, what I believe may have been Lamb Kabob, Falafel, Basmati Rice, half of a pita and some sort of Mint Salad. (please note order yourself an extra full pita if you like to eat pita with this type of food the price for one is pretty cheap :P)  I found the meats of the plate tasty, and left a pleasent long lasting spicy flavor on my palate that I have not experience quite a while. That I would consider mildly spicy. The only thing that I didn't really care for was the mint, just not a big fan of mint in general, so I can't really attest to how good the salad was. The pitas are excellent, get yourself an extra one.  The menu is 100% Zabinhah Halal according to their website. I would say definately go if you want  a different take on this region's type of food.

Today’s date is October 16, 2018. I was searching online for a middle eastern Restaurant as I am very familiar with the food. I called and asked to order a tabouli salad with chicken shawarma on top Since I do not eat bread or rice for my diet. The girl that answered the phone said they cannot do that. I then asked her how much is the chicken kabob skewer a la carte, she said $3.50 (I was thinking to jus order that with tabbouleh. But I told her I will look at the menu online and call back. I did call back about ten minutes later, before I took my lunch break and the same girl answered, I told her I would like to order one small side of hummus, one side of tabbouleh, a small order of falafel and one chicken kabob skewer. She said she can’t sell the chicken skewer alone, it has to be in a pita or a plate or on salad. I told her that I don’t eat bread or rice and I wanted to order it that way. She said OK I will do it for you this time And the skewer is $4.00. I told her I’m not interested in ordering and I’m going to be honest that was the worst first impression to try a place that is new to me. I I’m not telling the owner or manager what to do but I will say that it is unusual especially for Mediterranean or Middle Eastern restaurant to not offer to sell chicken kebab or beef kebab skewers a la carte. Some people don’t eat rice some people don’t eat bread and maybe some people don’t want to order it on a salad. The girl on the phone clearly has minimal experience in dealing with customers. Unfortunately I will not be trying this place.

The food was great! Me and a friend ordered a gyro, falafel, hummus, baklava, and extra pita to split. The falafel was my absolute favorite, it was so perfectly seasoned and crunchy!! The gyro was perfect, this one was lacking tomato (idk if that’s traditional) but it made it so much easier to eat. It was also filled in a pita instead of on top so it was easier to eat and less messy than most of my experiences! The pita for the hummus was a lot more bread-y than I was expecting, very fluffy. The hummus was eh. Way too light and mousse-y for my personal taste and it came in prepackaged plastic. Last but not least, the baklava was pretty good, not the greatest but still good!  Overall, would like to come back to this place one day for their perfect falafels and maybe not order the hummus.
